summary: im really frustrated by how many in the vegan community are so quick to react when a vegan public figure or prominent vegan...
question: im really frustrated by how many in the vegan community are so quick to react when a vegan public figure or prominent vegan youtuber is struggling w their veganism or stops being vegan. like we really shouldn't be doing this and certainly theres a problem with idolization and idealization of these ppl when they are also human and not perfect. i understand if it's a case of this person being antagonistic to begin w but if someone is clearly struggling maybe we should be sympathetic & not vengeful
answer:
I agree that people generally need to be having more constructive conversations with ex-vegans or those struggling with veganism, and I’ve written about that in some detail here. That said, I think part of the problem is that prominent people seem to rarely just say “this didn’t work for me because x y, z”, all too often that are going straight from vegan to anti-vegan, and launching straight into public criticism of veganism as movement and why other people should not attempt it. That sort of rhetoric absolutely should be opposed.

I think that we as a community need to get better at supporting people who are struggling or even totally failing in their veganism, but our patience for that can only go so far. Those who are struggling should be helped, but those actively seeking to sabotage veganism and spread misinformation about it in order to justify their own failures need to be opposed publicly, because they have the potential to do a great deal of damage to the movement.

I think that we as a community need to get better at supporting people who are struggling or even totally failing in their veganism, but our patience for that can only go so far. Those who are struggling should be helped, but those actively seeking to sabotage veganism and spread misinformation about it in order to justify their own failures need to be opposed publicly, because they have the potential to do a great deal of damage to the movement.

I agree that people generally need to be having more constructive conversations with ex-vegans or those struggling with veganism, and I’ve written about that in some detail here. That said, I think part of the problem is that prominent people seem to rarely just say “this didn’t work for me because x y, z”, all too often that are going straight from vegan to anti-vegan, and launching straight into public criticism of veganism as movement and why other people should not attempt it. That sort of rhetoric absolutely should be opposed.

I think that we as a community need to get better at supporting people who are struggling or even totally failing in their veganism, but our patience for that can only go so far. Those who are struggling should be helped, but those actively seeking to sabotage veganism and spread misinformation about it in order to justify their own failures need to be opposed publicly, because they have the potential to do a great deal of damage to the movement.
